    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2895261870" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2895261870" />
    <a title="Sylvie " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/64899539-sylvie"><img alt="Sylvie " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610841583p2/64899539.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2895261870?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sylvie " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sylvie " href="/user/show/64899539-sylvie">Sylvie </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780763676193" href="/book/show/20758105-monsters-of-men">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64899539-sylvie?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64899539-sylvie?shelf=dystopian">dystopian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2895261870" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12812602313104368313"><b>
  <u>Attention. This review will contain spoilers, especially if you haven&apos;t read the first two books!</u>
</b><br/><br/><i>“It&apos;s not how we fall. It&apos;s how we get back up again.”</i><br/><br/>After finishing Ask and Answer I was a teeny tiny bit dissappinted in the series. More explanation: Yes, I still did like it, but did I like it more than The Knife of Never Letting Go? No way! The first book was very unique and original and amazing in every possible way. However, that doesn&apos;t mean I didn&apos;t live through pain and agony in the se</span>
  <span id="freeText12812602313104368313" style="display:none"><b>
  <u>Attention. This review will contain spoilers, especially if you haven't read the first two books!</u>
</b><br /><br /><i>“It's not how we fall. It's how we get back up again.”</i><br /><br />After finishing Ask and Answer I was a teeny tiny bit dissappinted in the series. More explanation: Yes, I still did like it, but did I like it more than The Knife of Never Letting Go? No way! The first book was very unique and original and amazing in every possible way. However, that doesn't mean I didn't live through pain and agony in the second book, but mostly at the end. <br />The difference with the first two books were that the first one was more fun and intriguing to read though the second one was more stressful yet more bland?<br />Moving on the third and last installement: I thought it would leave me with a slight disappointement like it did in the second book but Patrick Ness proved me wrong and I was happy for that, it was just what I needed. Action, angst, lots of adventure and of course the never ending agony that I felt throughout the entire book.<br /><br />One of the things that I found weird and interesting in the first book was everytime I saw words which were written incorrectly I used to think that it was a typo or an editing problem but it wasn't. (Because the boys never learned how to read nor write in Prentisstown.) It’s kind of funny that the author kept that whole thing going through the trilogy, because it shows the uniqueness of the writing and we as in readers can experience how Todd thinks that the words should be written.<br /><br />I still can't wrap my mind around Todd and Viola's ages. I mean they're only 13/14 and their stratigies were way better than the older people who had way more eperience than them. But, I also have a positive and negative thing to say about their friendship/relationship:<br />I loved how close they become in the series, how they trusted and relied on each other. It was too pure and sweet. <br /><br /><u>Unpopular opinion:</u><br />Although them being only in their early teens they loved each other truly, madly, deeply and most importantly romantically. That kind of threw me off a bit. Like, they're just children, they're not even 16 or so. Anyway, I didn't let that minor part ruin the trilogy for me.<br />Also, Viola gets irritated whenever she can't hear Todd's noise. She was being selfish about that, because both of them together and as apart from each other have been through so much yet there was lack of trust from Violet's side towards Todd.<br /><br />Oh and the mayor? He just made the number 1 on my list of fictional book villains who are psychopaths on extreme level. Here's why:<br />The entire relationship with Todd and the mayor in Monster of Men was creepy, weird, manipulative and very unsettling. The mayor killed his own son without thinking about it for a second and replaced him with Todd just like that. I mean if that doesn’t scream psychopath I don’t know what else. I guess, he saw more “potential of a son” in Todd and then tried to have the impact of a father figure on him. <br /><br />What I find confusing at first was the 3rd pov but after a couple of chapters of that it became normal. Before the Chaos Trilogy, I have read PoVs like that in Starbound series by Amie Kaufman and Meagan Spooner, and that also was very confusing at first but the more I read those chapters the more intriguing they have become, thus it wasn't a first time experience for me.<br /><br />This entire trilogy was a solid 4 stars for me, and in my opinion that's a pretty reasonable rating. There were scenes, characters and incidents that I found unnecessary or wasn't fan of them, but that didn't stop me from not loving the series.<br /><br />If u like sci-fi/dystopian, action-packed adventures and strong characters then I highly recommend this trilogy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12812602313104368313" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


