        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3879787386" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5757803525954233841">Patrick Ness’ modus operandi for Monsters of Men seems to be: take your absolute worst nightmare, multiply it by infinity, set it on fire, poke it and make it angry , and then blindfold yourself so that it has the advantage over you in a fight. Everything that could go wrong, goes wrong at the worst possible time. Neither you nor the characters will catch a break as Ness takes our protagonists, Todd and Viola, on a perilous journey that rivals Samwise and Frodo’s quest to destroy the One Ring. I</span>
  <span id="freeText5757803525954233841" style="display:none">Patrick Ness’ modus operandi for Monsters of Men seems to be: take your absolute worst nightmare, multiply it by infinity, set it on fire, poke it and make it angry , and then blindfold yourself so that it has the advantage over you in a fight. Everything that could go wrong, goes wrong at the worst possible time. Neither you nor the characters will catch a break as Ness takes our protagonists, Todd and Viola, on a perilous journey that rivals Samwise and Frodo’s quest to destroy the One Ring. It’s wildly entertaining with a mix of suspense, political intrigue, and philosophical musings. Take a deep breath and preemptively cancel all your plans before you start this trilogy. <br /><br />Buddy read with the lovely <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/58704775-katie" rel="nofollow noopener">Katie</a>. Thank you for putting up with the walls of text. </span>
